<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877177" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6877177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877177/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" startId="6.[151,250,1183,1207]" targetBox="[151,1435,181,1159]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1183,1243]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,277,1183,1207]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">FIGURE 5.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Lapointe &amp; Watling, 2022" authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[285,487,1183,1207]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Keratoisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="fruticosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[285,487,1183,1207]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">Keratoisis fruticosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[495,552,1183,1206]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
body sclerites of paratype specimens, A, K3837, B, K3851, C, K3850, D, K3836, E, K3838, F, K3844.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="143" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1289,2000]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1289,1315]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Colony is bushy in appearance, branching irregularly at the internodes, occasionally with nodes at the origin of the branch. Secondary calcification occurs over most of the axis. Sclerites in the polyp body are needles or rods arranged obliquely, longitudinally, and occasionally horizontally at the base. Septal sclerites are arranged in groups or as single longitudinal needles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="145" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1289,2000]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,476,1433,1459]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">
Description of 
<typeStatus box="[373,476,1433,1459]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">holotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
. Branching pattern is irregular. Colony branches at the internodes, but a node might be present at the origin of the branch (
<figureCitation box="[541,630,1469,1495]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,814,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-224@4.[154,1434,814,1925]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp., holotype, K3832, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony being collected, C, D, views of individual polyps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877169" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877169/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
). The axis is approximately 
<quantity box="[944,1022,1469,1496]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" unit="mm" value="15.0">15 mm</quantity>
in diameter at the base of the colony, and decreases to 
<quantity box="[342,407,1505,1532]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
at the distal branches. The axis core is hollow, pin-sized throughout the entire colony, independent of the diameter of the axis.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1289,2000]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">
Internodes range from 
<quantity box="[456,600,1577,1604]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.55" metricValueMax="5.9" metricValueMin="3.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" unit="mm" value="45.5" valueMax="59.0" valueMin="32.0">32 to 59 mm</quantity>
in length. Polyps are located on all sides of the axis, separated by obvious coenenchyme tissue. Polyps are tall (~ 
<quantity box="[586,640,1613,1639]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" unit="cm" value="1.0">1 cm</quantity>
) and columnar, with a similar diameter throughout (
<figureCitation box="[1227,1350,1613,1639]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,814,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-224@4.[154,1434,814,1925]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp., holotype, K3832, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony being collected, C, D, views of individual polyps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877169" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877169/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">Fig. 3C, D</figureCitation>
). Sclerites in the polyp body are rods and needles, and may be straight or slightly curved, ranging in length from 0.55 to 4.0 mm. Sclerites are arranged obliquely and longitudinally throughout the polyp body, and occasionally horizontally at the base (
<figureCitation box="[286,440,1721,1747]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,814,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-224@4.[154,1434,814,1925]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp., holotype, K3832, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony being collected, C, D, views of individual polyps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877169" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877169/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">Figure 3C, D</figureCitation>
). Rods and needles have longitudinal grooves and tuberculate ends (
<figureCitation box="[1212,1303,1721,1747]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1667,1691]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1642]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1435,181,1643]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp., holotype, K3832, sclerites from, A, polyp body, B, coenenchyme, C, tentacles, and D, pharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877173" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877173/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Scales are not present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1289,2000]" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">
Septal sclerites are needles arranged in groups or singly, perpendicular to the polyp axis, and flare outward slightly when tentacles are contracted. When contracted, tentacles fold slightly inward with tips touching, or fold over slightly toward the center of the polyp (
<figureCitation box="[657,746,1865,1891]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1948,1972]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,814,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-224@4.[154,1434,814,1925]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp., holotype, K3832, A, all collected and preserved colony pieces, B, in situ view of colony being collected, C, D, views of individual polyps." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877169" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877169/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Tentacular sclerites are rods and flat rods, ranging from approximately 
<quantity box="[294,482,1901,1928]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" unit="mm" value="0.52" valueMax="0.75" valueMin="0.29">0.29 to 0.75 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[498,588,1901,1927]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1667,1691]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1642]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1435,181,1643]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp., holotype, K3832, sclerites from, A, polyp body, B, coenenchyme, C, tentacles, and D, pharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877173" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877173/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="143">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). The larger rods are arranged longitudinally along the tentacles, decorated with grooves, and have rounded ends with numerous tubercles. The pinnules contain smaller flat rods, 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="1.5" metricValueMin="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="143" unit="mm" value="0.125" valueMax="0.15" valueMin="0.1">0.10 to 0.15 mm</quantity>
, also decorated with longitudinal grooves and numerous tubercles.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877179" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6877179" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877179/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="144" startId="7.[151,250,1046,1070]" targetBox="[238,1350,182,1022]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1046,1106]" pageId="7" pageNumber="144">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,278,1046,1070]" pageId="7" pageNumber="144">FIGURE 6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Lapointe &amp; Watling, 2022" authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[288,492,1046,1070]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Keratoisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="7" pageNumber="144" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="fruticosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[288,492,1046,1070]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="144">Keratoisis fruticosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[501,559,1047,1070]" pageId="7" pageNumber="144" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
coenenchyme sclerites of paratype specimens, A, K3837, B, K3851, C, K3850, D, K3836, E, K3838, F, K3844.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877183" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6877183" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877183/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="144" startId="7.[151,250,1981,2005]" targetBox="[243,1345,1130,1957]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1981,2042]" pageId="7" pageNumber="144">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1981,2006]" pageId="7" pageNumber="144">FIGURE 7.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Lapointe &amp; Watling, 2022" authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[282,483,1982,2006]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Keratoisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="7" pageNumber="144" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="fruticosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[282,483,1982,2006]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="144">Keratoisis fruticosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[490,545,1982,2005]" pageId="7" pageNumber="144" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
tentacle sclerites of paratype specimens, A, K3837, B, K3851, C, K3850, D, K3836, E, K3838, F, K3844.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877185" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6877185" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877185/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" startId="8.[151,250,1032,1056]" targetBox="[241,1345,181,1006]" targetPageId="8">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1032,1092]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1032,1056]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">FIGURE 8.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Lapointe &amp; Watling, 2022" authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[281,482,1032,1056]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Keratoisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="fruticosa" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[281,482,1032,1056]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Keratoisis fruticosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[488,543,1032,1055]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
pharyngeal sclerites of paratype specimens, A, K3837, B, K3851, C, K3850, D, K3836, E, K3838, F, K3844.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1138,2029]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">
Sclerites of the pharynx are irregularly toothed rods, with a heavily textured surface decorated with longitudinal grooves and multiple tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[518,611,1174,1200]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1667,1691]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1642]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1435,181,1643]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp., holotype, K3832, sclerites from, A, polyp body, B, coenenchyme, C, tentacles, and D, pharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877173" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877173/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). Lateral teeth may be gently rounded or triangular. Pharyngeal sclerites range in length from approximately 
<quantity box="[551,735,1210,1237]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="7" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" unit="mm" value="0.085" valueMax="0.1" valueMin="0.07">0.07 to 0.10 mm</quantity>
, and two sclerites may occasionally be fused together. Sclerites in the form of rods, similar in size and shape to sclerites in the polyp body, are sparsely and irregularly arranged throughout the coenenchyme (
<figureCitation box="[492,580,1282,1308]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1667,1691]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1642]" captionTargetId="figure-19@5.[151,1435,181,1643]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 4. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp., holotype, K3832, sclerites from, A, polyp body, B, coenenchyme, C, tentacles, and D, pharynx." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877173" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877173/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1138,2029]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,474,1318,1344]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">
Variation of 
<typeStatus box="[356,474,1318,1344]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">paratypes</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
. All specimens examined and designated as 
<typeStatus box="[996,1103,1319,1345]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">paratypes</typeStatus>
had genetically identical sequences for the gene mtMutS. Axis internodes vary significantly in length, both within and between the specimens collected. Internodes are most frequently between 30 and 
<quantity box="[807,887,1390,1417]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" unit="mm" value="50.0">50 mm</quantity>
in length, but there is great variation in distance between nodes, ranging from 
<quantity box="[490,639,1426,1453]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" metricValueMax="7.0" metricValueMin="1.8" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" unit="mm" value="44.0" valueMax="70.0" valueMin="18.0">18 to 70 mm</quantity>
. In specimen TMAG K3851, several portions of the axis form anastomoses.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1138,2029]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">
Needle sclerites in the polyp body and coenenchyme are often straight, but most of the specimens collected commonly have curved sclerites in these areas (
<figureCitation box="[690,759,1534,1561]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1183,1207]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1159]" captionTargetId="figure-25@6.[151,1435,181,1159]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 5. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp. body sclerites of paratype specimens, A, K3837, B, K3851, C, K3850, D, K3836, E, K3838, F, K3844." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877177" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877177/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). In TMAG K3837, flat rods were also found irregularly arranged in the coenenchyme, similar in shape and decoration to the flat rods in the tentacles, but slightly larger (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1046,1070]" captionTargetBox="[238,1350,182,1022]" captionTargetId="figure-19@7.[238,1350,181,1022]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp. coenenchyme sclerites of paratype specimens, A, K3837, B, K3851, C, K3850, D, K3836, E, K3838, F, K3844." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877179" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877179/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Tentacular sclerites always consist of rods and flat rods, although the larger rods may vary slightly in shape (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[243,1345,1130,1957]" captionTargetId="figure-47@7.[243,1345,1130,1957]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 7. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp. tentacle sclerites of paratype specimens, A, K3837, B, K3851, C, K3850, D, K3836, E, K3838, F, K3844." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877183" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877183/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Some may have a pronounced club appearance, while others may be wider in the middle than at the ends. Specimens TMAG K3848, TMAG K3850 and TMAG K3844 have pharyngeal sclerites similar in size and shape to the other specimens collected, but with several very sharp extensions protruding from the sclerites (
<figureCitation box="[1225,1293,1714,1740]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1032,1056]" captionTargetBox="[241,1345,181,1006]" captionTargetId="figure-25@8.[241,1346,181,1007]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 8. Keratoisis fruticosa n. sp. pharyngeal sclerites of paratype specimens, A, K3837, B, K3851, C, K3850, D, K3836, E, K3838, F, K3844." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877185" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877185/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="145" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1138,2029]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1750,1776]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name based on the Latin adjective 
<emphasis box="[785,905,1750,1776]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">fruticosum</emphasis>
, = bushy or shrubby, a reference to the general appearance of the colony.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="145" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1138,2029]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1822,1848]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species is unique in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wright" authorityYear="1869" box="[749,864,1823,1848]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Keratoisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[749,864,1823,1848]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Keratoisis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as the branching pattern is highly variable, with branches at the internodes, but with nodes at the origin of some of the branches. Interestingly, that mode of branching was also illustrated for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wright" authorityYear="1869" box="[456,548,1895,1920]" class="Anthozoa" family="Isididae" genus="Keratoisis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="grayi">
<emphasis box="[456,548,1895,1920]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">K. grayi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bayer, F. M." box="[591,742,1894,1921]" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" refId="ref8947" refString="Bayer, F. M. (1956) Octocorallia. Treatise on Invertebrate Paleontology, Part F, F 166 - F 231." type="journal volume" year="1956">Bayer (1956)</bibRefCitation>
. This species also demonstrates high variability in the sclerite shape, in particular in the body and coenenchyme. Various invertebrates tend to be associated with this species. An anemone was growing on one of the branches of TMAG K3837 and was included in the specimen collection. TMAG K3850 was collected growing on the dead skeleton of a scleractinian coral, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duncan" authorityYear="1873" box="[1087,1346,2002,2028]" class="Anthozoa" family="Caryophylliidae" genus="Solenosmilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scleractinia" pageId="8" pageNumber="145" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="variabilis">
<emphasis box="[1087,1346,2002,2028]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="145">Solenosmilia variabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
